# Fixing GitHub Authentication Error

GitHub no longer accepts your account password for terminal operations. You must use a **Personal Access Token (PAT)** instead.

## How to Generate a Token
1.  Go to [GitHub Settings > Developer settings > Personal access tokens > Tokens (classic)](https://github.com/settings/tokens).
2.  Click **Generate new token (classic)**.
3.  Give it a name (e.g., "SustainaBuy-Release").
4.  Select the **repo** scope (this allows pushing code).
5.  Click **Generate token** at the bottom.
6.  **Copy the token immediately!** (You won't see it again).

## How to Push with the Token
When you run the push command and it asks for a password, **paste the token instead of your password**.

```bash
git push origin main --tags
```

- **Username**: `sarang-cmd`
- **Password**: `[PASTE_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE]`

> [!TIP]
> If you want to avoid typing the token every time, you can tell Git to cache your credentials:
> ```bash
> git config --global credential.helper osxkeychain
> ```

## Alternative: SSH (Recommended for long-term)
If you prefer not to use tokens, I can help you set up an SSH key. Let me know if you want to try that!
